<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-528-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 528 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  August 14 1989 v11 n33 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Business computing abroad: a mixed bag.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lee, Yvonne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Language and cultural differences, as well as differing economicstructures, make business computing in foreign countries asdifferent as the countries themselves.andP;  The availability oftechnology varies from country to country, and softwarecompatibility is a major problem.andP;  Users can choose frominternational products or local products, depending on the needfor international compatibility and availability.andP;  Foreignlanguages are often difficult to program for, and popular softwarepackages may not have local versions.andP;  Operating systems are morestandardized at present, with DOS being the clear standard inmicrocomputing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     InternationalWorld MarketCompatibilityBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>